years = data.year.unique()
row = 0
col = 0
total_year = len(years)
total_country = len(data.country.unique())
#2D list of life expectancy over year
life_exp_per_year = [[0]*total_country for rows in range(total_year)]

while row < len(data.lifeExp):
    for i in range(total_year):
        life_exp_per_year[i][col] = data['lifeExp'][col*len(years)+i]
    row += total_year
    col += 1

Question 1: The general trend for life expectancy across time is increasing based on the scatter plot and violin plot created above and it seems that the trend is linear.

Question 2: According to the violin plot, it looks like the distribution is bottom skewed over time, meaning that life expectancy across countries is increasing, and the plot is going from bimodal to unimodal. If considering mean value as the center, the distribution is not symmetric around its center.

Question 3: I might reject the null hypothesis of no relationship. Since life expectancy can be affected by various factors, which the most obvious one is the advancement of medical technology, there should be some sort of relationship between life expectancy and year. Also, the plots above show that life expectancy is increasing over time.

Question 4: Since residual is the differences between observed and predicted values (regression line) of data and the distribution of the life expectancy data wont change, the violin plot of residuals vs year and the linear model from Q3 will look pretty much the same.

Question 5: If there is a linear relationship between life expectancy and year, then we can say that there are dense plot points around the regression line. Therefore, the violin plots should look unimodal and and symmetric around the predicted values.

slope = model.coef_[0][0]

print("Slope:", slope)

for name, group in continent_group:
    ax = group.plot(x='year', y='lifeExp', kind='scatter', xlabel=("Year"), ylabel=("Life Expectancy"), figsize=(10, 6))
    ax.set_title("{} Life Expectancy vs Year Plot".format(group.iloc[0][1]))
    ax.set_ylim(20,90)
    
    #Create linear regression line for each plot
    trend = np.polyfit(group['year'], group['lifeExp'], 1)
    print("{} regression line slope: {} ".format(group.iloc[0][1], trend[0]))
    poly = np.poly1d(trend)
    x = np.linspace(1950, 2010)
    y = poly(x)
    plt.plot(x, y, 'g--')
    plt.show()

mean_group = data.groupby(['continent', 'year'])
#2D list of mean life expectancy over year
mean_life_exp_per_year = []
mean_year_group = []

for name, group in mean_group:
    mean = group.lifeExp.sum()/len(group)
    mean_life_exp_per_year.append(mean)
    mean_year_group.append(group.iloc[0][2])

mean_residual_per_year = [[0]*len(continents) for x in range(total_year)]
row = 0
col = 0

for name, group in mean_group:
    mean = group.residual.sum()/len(group)
    mean_residual_per_year[row][col] = mean
    row += 1
    if row == total_year:
        row = 0
        col += 1
        
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10, 6))

ax.set_xlabel("Year")
ax.set_ylabel("Residual")
ax.set_title("Residual of Life Expectancy vs Year Interaction Model Violin Plot")
plt.show()

#Get two features from the wine dataset (alcohol and color_intensity columns) and run the Linear SVM algorithm
attributes = wine_data.data[:, (9, 0)]
svm_two_features_model = svm.SVC(kernel="linear")
svm_two_features_model = svm_two_features_model.fit(attributes, wine_data.target)
classes = svm_two_features_model.classes_

#test if the model works as expected
#print(svm_model.predict(np.reshape([14.16, 9.700000], (1, -1))))

#create seperating hyperplanes for each class
a=[]
for i in classes:
    a.append(-svm_two_features_model.coef_[i, 0]/svm_two_features_model.coef_[i, 1])

x_predict = np.linspace(0, 13.5)
y_predict = []
for i in classes:
    y_predict.append(a[i] * x_predict - svm_two_features_model.intercept_[i]/svm_two_features_model.coef_[i, 1])

The wine dataset I used is provided by SKLearn, it includes three classes (class_0, class_1 and class_2) and 13 different attribites for each class. I tried to predict the class that a wine belongs to based on its attribute values. For the first two prediction models, I only considered two features from the dataset, which are alcohol and color intensity. On the other hand, all features are considered in the third and fourth model.

Since there are three different classes for this dataset, it makes more sense to pick classifiers to predict the performance. The two algorithms I chose to train the dataset are Linear Discriminant Analysis and Linear SVM. To get a better sense on how the data points spread on a 2d graph, I trained the data with only two features first. Based on the first plot, it looks like the LDA model with two features do fairly well outside the domain (-1, 1) and range(-2, 1). For the linear SVM model with two features, the hyperplanes seperate each class's data points quite well, along with some ambiguity at domain (4, 6) and range (12.5, 13.5).

After testing out the models with two features, I used LDA for dimensionality reduction since it becomes more difficult to visualize high dimensional data (13 dimensions in this case). The data is transformed after running the LDA fit method and it can be visualized by creating the scatter plot. According to the LDA plot, we can find out that the model did a good job on identifying data points by class type. I selected Linear SVM because it seems that the clusters can be well seperated by lines according to the LDA plot. The last plot shows that the Linear SVM model works well on the dataset, which the dataset's dimension has been reducted by LDA.

In [225]:
#Apply holdout validation
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(wine_data.data, wine_data.target, test_size=0.4, random_state=0)
lda_model = LinearDiscriminantAnalysis()
lda_model = lda_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
lda_predict = lda_model.predict(X_test)

svm_model = svm.SVC(kernel="linear")
svm_model = svm_model.fit(X_train, y_train)
svm_predict = svm_model.predict(X_test)

classes = ['class_0', 'class_1', 'class_2']
#matrix_lda = confusion_matrix(lda_predict, y_test)
#matrix_svm = confusion_matrix(svm_predict, y_test)

print("LDA performance metric")
print(classification_report(y_test, lda_predict, target_names = classes) + "\n")
print("Linear SVM performance metric")
print(classification_report(y_test, svm_predict, target_names = classes))

              precision    recall  f1-score   support

     class_0       1.00      1.00      1.00        22

     class_2       0.86      1.00      0.93        19

    accuracy                           0.96        72
   macro avg       0.95      0.97      0.96        72
weighted avg       0.96      0.96      0.96        72

For the accuracy of positive predictions, i.e., precision, LDA does way better than SVM on class_2, SVM does slightly better than LDA on class_0 and both models did perfect on class_1.

For the ability to find all positive instances, i.e., recall, they both did perfect on identifying the positives of class_0 and class_2, while LDA did slightly better on class_1.

According to the definition of f1-score, "the closer the value of the f1-score is to 1.0, the better the expected performance of the model is". The LDA model performed quite well on all three classes, while SVM performed better on class_0 and class_1 compare to class_2.
